"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1131750","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-06-17","<p>As at 30 September 2018, 40% of those persons in receipt of State Pension who reached their State Pension date prior to 6<sup>th</sup> April 2016, who had previously deferred their claims, had received Lump Sum payments.</p><p> </p><p><em>Source: DWP Administrative data – Quarterly Statistical Enquiry September 2018</em></p><p> </p><p>The specific information on <strong>how many people who reached State Pension age before 6 April 2016 continue to defer claiming their State Pension,</strong> is not available.</p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman",,"2019-06-17T14:30:32.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1131750/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1131750/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1131750/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-06-12","State Retirement Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people who reached state pension age before 6 April 2016 continue to defer claiming their state pension; and what proportion of people who have claimed deferred pre-6 April 2016 state pensions have taken a lump sum rather than an increased state pension.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","263665"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1131751","Department for Education","false","2019-06-21","<p>Details on interventions by the UK Statistics Authority (UKSA) are published in the correspondence<a href="https://educationgovuk.sharepoint.com/sites/cd/c/WorkplaceDocuments/Written%20PQ%20Team/Written%20PQ%20-%202017-19%20drafts/263724%20QC%20140619.docx#_ftn1" target="_blank">[1]</a>, publications<a href="https://educationgovuk.sharepoint.com/sites/cd/c/WorkplaceDocuments/Written%20PQ%20Team/Written%20PQ%20-%202017-19%20drafts/263724%20QC%20140619.docx#_ftn2" target="_blank">[2]</a>, and issues log<a href="https://educationgovuk.sharepoint.com/sites/cd/c/WorkplaceDocuments/Written%20PQ%20Team/Written%20PQ%20-%202017-19%20drafts/263724%20QC%20140619.docx#_ftn3" target="_blank">[3]</a> sections of their website since 2010.</p><p> </p><p>The UKSA’s Office for Statistics Regulation also carry out regular assessments and systemic reviews, details of which can also be found on the UKSA’s website<a href="https://educationgovuk.sharepoint.com/sites/cd/c/WorkplaceDocuments/Written%20PQ%20Team/Written%20PQ%20-%202017-19%20drafts/263724%20QC%20140619.docx#_ftn4" target="_blank">[4]</a>.</p><p> </p><p>In September 2018, the UKSA published the first annual summary of its interventions for the financial year 2017/18<a href="https://educationgovuk.sharepoint.com/sites/cd/c/WorkplaceDocuments/Written%20PQ%20Team/Written%20PQ%20-%202017-19%20drafts/263724%20QC%20140619.docx#_ftn5" target="_blank">[5]</a>. The report for 2018/19 will be published in the autumn.</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://educationgovuk.sharepoint.com/sites/cd/c/WorkplaceDocuments/Written%20PQ%20Team/Written%20PQ%20-%202017-19%20drafts/263724%20QC%20140619.docx#_ftnref1" target="_blank">[1]</a> <a href="https://www.statisticsauthority.gov.uk/correspondence-list/" target="_blank">https://www.statisticsauthority.gov.uk/correspondence-list/</a>.</p><p><a href="https://educationgovuk.sharepoint.com/sites/cd/c/Workplace